Patch Set 1:

WebOb is not considering adding support for Chunked Encoding because there is no support for it in the WSGI specification, there is no good way to support it.

If you know that your server properly provides an EOF marker when reading from environ['wsgi.input'], then you can set environ['webob.is_body_readable'] to True and WebOb will bypass the check for environ['CONTENT_LENGTH'] (which is required by the WSGI specification, but can't be set if there is a Transfer Encoding, which is a Hop-by-Hop which is not supported by WSGI).

This was done due to compatibility issues with `wsgiref` and other potential WSGI servers, and previously WebOb also wouldn't allow a body on DELETE for example, or on GET (which was/is used by ElasticSearch).

See this PR for more information: https://github.com/Pylons/webob/pull/283

My recommendation, set 'webob.is_body_readable' in the WSGI environ, and make sure that the server used works with the example provided in the Github link above.

Patch Set 1:

BTW, setting 'webob.is_body_readable' in the environ will work for Webob 1.6 and 1.7.

Patch Set 10: Code-Review+1

I prefer PS10.  It's much more clear what's going on.

Patch Set 10:

PS 8 avoids setting of the is_body_readable flag in 2 different places, which to me feels more readable and simple. (Call a method in wsgi and it will take care of things). This is especially better if in the future we have to perform the checks and we have all the work done in one class method in wsgi.py.
That said, code wise, currently both achieve the same goal.

Patch Set 10: Code-Review+2

I did a little smoke testing with updated requirements and didn't find any issues in this implementation. (famous last words)

The difference between PS8 and this is a matter of taste, and I strongly respect Dharini's point. I would be +2 on either at this point. This one is in front of me now and it works so I'm voting. If we flip to the PS8 style I'll vote again.

Patch Set 10:

I appreciate Dharini's point that PS10 has the same code in 2 place.  I think my problem with PS8 is mostly the name of the function--I find it counterintuitive that a method named '_decide_request_body_readable' that takes an object as a parameter modifies one of the fields of the object as a side effect.  Maybe if it had a more perspicuous name I'd like it better.

Patch Set 10:

> I appreciate Dharini's point that PS10 has the same code in 2
 > place.  I think my problem with PS8 is mostly the name of the
 > function--I find it counterintuitive that a method named
 > '_decide_request_body_readable' that takes an object as a parameter
 > modifies one of the fields of the object as a side effect.  Maybe
 > if it had a more perspicuous name I'd like it better.

That name is definitely absurd. And, like you correctly point out, it is absurd because of its overloaded nature. Functions that return boolean typically don't modify object state. They just introspect the object for certain conditions and report True/False. 

If we modify the object state, it is counter-intuitive. I'd even say it's a code smell. Let's say we call this method "is_body_readable". How does it make sense for a method called "is_body_readable" to modify the state of the object passed as an argument to it? Imagine invoking this method at different parts of the code with an implicit expectation that the object state be modified accordingly.

Thus, I've decided to get rid of the implicitness in favor of ugly explicitness. Also, what we are doing here is ugly in the sense that we are working around something that is not supported in wsgi spec. If we are doing something that isn't a standard way of doing things, I'd rather do it explicitly. Maybe I should add a note.

Anyway, that's my take on this. But, if majority of the reviewers feel otherwise, I'm open to reverting to PS8 albeit with reservations.

Patch Set 10: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

Let's go with PS10 for the reasons Hemanth has outlined.  Dims is getting impatient (this is blocking a requirements change), so let's just go with PS10 for now.  If anyone feels strongly about PS8, please put up a follow-up patch and we can argue about it there.
